<h5 id="before_you_start">Before you start</h5>
<div class="level5">

<p>
This will deactivate dnsmasq and with it will disable automatic creation of your internal hostnames (&quot;lan&quot; or &quot;intra&quot; or whatever your named it). You will need to managed the zone files yourself.
</p>

<p>
This allows you to managed your local <abbr title="Domain Name System">DNS</abbr> using bind and also provide a public <abbr title="Domain Name System">DNS</abbr> server at the same time. Your local lan can still use your router as a <abbr title="Domain Name System">DNS</abbr> server for public and local <abbr title="Domain Name System">DNS</abbr> queries.
</p>

<p>
This tutorial used &quot;.intra.&quot; as internal hostname suffix and the internal network address 172.20.0.0/16. Also the tutorial assumes you have some experience with bind.
</p>

</div>

<h5 id="installation">Installation</h5>
<div class="level5">

<p>
Install at least the following packages:
 * bind-server
 * bind-tools
</p>

<p>
Deactivate the <abbr title="Domain Name System">DNS</abbr> functionality of dnsmasq by setting &quot;port&quot; to &quot;0&quot;.
</p>

<p>
From this point on you will need &quot;bind&quot; for <abbr title="Domain Name System">DNS</abbr> forwarding and internal hostnames.
</p>

<p>
Copy the file &quot;/etc/named.conf.example&quot; to &quot;/etc/named.conf&quot; and perform the following steps:
 * Add your ISPs name servers to the &quot;forwarders section&quot; if you like to use them. Bind can also work without these since it can perform lookups using the global dns servers.
 * Add two zone files (&quot;.intra&quot; and &quot;.172&quot;)
</p>

</div>

<h4 id="local_zone_files">Local Zone Files</h4>
<div class="level4">

</div>

<h3 class="sectionedit1" id="etcbindnamedconf">/etc/bind/named.conf</h3>
<div class="level3">

<p>
add:
<pre class="code"> zone &quot;intra&quot; {
        type master;
        file &quot;/etc/bind/zone.intra&quot;;
 };                       

 zone &quot;172.in-addr.arpa&quot; {
        type master;
        file &quot;/etc/bind/zone.172&quot;;
 }; </pre>

</p>

</div>

<h3 class="sectionedit2" id="etcbindzoneintra">/etc/bind/zone.intra</h3>
<div class="level3">

<p>
<pre class="code">;
$TTL	604800
@	IN	SOA	intra. root.intra. (
			      1		; Serial
			 604800		; Refresh
			  86400		; Retry
			2419200		; Expire
			 604800 )	; Negative Cache TTL
;
@		IN	NS	router.intra.
@		IN	A	172.20.1.1
router		IN	A	172.20.1.1
host2		IN	A	172.20.1.2</pre>

</p>

</div>

<h3 class="sectionedit3" id="etcbindzone172">/etc/bind/zone.172</h3>
<div class="level3">

<p>
<pre class="code">;
$TTL	604800
@	IN	SOA	intra. root.intra. (
			      1		; Serial
			 604800		; Refresh
			  86400		; Retry
			2419200		; Expire
			 604800 )	; Negative Cache TTL
;
@		IN	NS	router.intra.
1.1.20		IN	PTR	router.intra.
2.1.20		IN	PTR	host2.intra.</pre>

</p>

<p>
Note that the IP addresses are reversed
</p>

</div>

<h5 id="test">Test</h5>
<div class="level5">

<p>
<pre class="code">dig ANY intra @localhost</pre>

</p>

<p>
should provide you with a valid response of your domain &quot;intra&quot;.
</p>

</div>

<h5 id="finally">Finally</h5>
<div class="level5">

<p>
&quot;enable&quot; and &quot;start&quot; /etc/init.d/named.
</p>

</div>

